[1] Cholera - Namibia (Ohangwena)
Date: Mon 31 Mar 2008
Source: AllAfrica & New Era (Windhoek) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200803310451.html>


Cholera has claimed 3 lives at Engela State Hospital while 727
suspected cases of cholera have been reported in the Ohangwena
Region, with 16 confirmed cholera cases, said the Regional Health
Director Dr. Naftal Hamata.

[Byline: Anna Ingwafa]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of Namibia showing the province of Ohangwena in the north can
be found at <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohangwena>. It borders the
Angolan province of Cunene, which has had cholera activity as well. - Mod.LL]

*****
[2] Cholera - Kenya (Nyanza, Western provinces)
Date: Mon 31 Mar 2008
Source: AllAfrica & The East African Standard (Nairobi) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200803310989.html>


39 people in Nyanza Province have succumbed to cholera since January
2008. More than 450 cases have been reported in hospitals in the same period.

The Nyanza Provincial Medical Officer, Dr. Jackson Kioko, said the
epidemic began in Suba and Siaya districts. "The outbreak then spread
to Homa Bay District and Kisumu," Kioko said.

He said health workers had contained the outbreak in Siaya and Rongo,
adding that Migori District was particularly hard hit with more than
10 deaths reported. "We had 30 cases last week, while a similar
number of patients are seeking treatment in various health centres in
the district," he said.

Kioko added that the influx of displaced people and feasting at
funerals contributed to the spread of cholera. "We are asking
residents to stop holding extended funerals to reduce the amount of
food prepared," he said.

The Provincial Public Health Officer, Mr. Tom Andebe, said that
improper disposal of human waste was another contributing factor.
"Only about 30 percent of residents have built pit latrines. People
defecate in bushes," he said. The official added that rain often
washed human stool into water sources.

"In areas where cholera is prevalent, residents use water from dams
and rivers without boiling it," said Andebe.

Meanwhile, a cholera outbreak has been reported in Budalang'i,
Western Province. Western Provincial Medical Officer, Dr. Onudu
Olang'o, yesterday [30 Mar 2008] said 7 people were undergoing
treatment at Port Victoria Sub-District Hospital.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Nyanza and Western provinces have a common border in western Kenya
and can be seen on a map of the country at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/kenya.pdf>

