*****
[7] Diarrhea, cholera - Viet Nam (north)
Date: Thu 27 Mar 2008
Source: VietNamNet [edited]
<http://english.vietnamnet.vn/social/2008/03/775639/>


The Health Ministry on 27 Mar 2008 reported 2 more provinces in the
north, Bac Ninh and Bac Kan, have acute diarrhea patients, raising
the number of localities with this disease to 5. Most of the
patients in Bac Ninh and Bac Kan caught acute diarrhea after eating
raw vegetables, shrimp paste or blood pudding.

Hai Phong still has the lead in the number of patients, 12, followed
by Hanoi with 9. The Health Ministry warned that acute diarrhea could
break out into an epidemic this summer and asked provinces and cities
to tighten control of food safety, especially street food and risky
foods, and to raise people's awareness of food hygiene.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[At least in part, this outbreak is due to cholera as previously
reported. Bac Ninh and Bac Kan (Bac Can on the map) can be found on a
map at: <http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>. - Mod.LL]

*****
[8] Dysentery - Papua New Guinea (Morobe)
Date: Thu 27 Mar 2008
Source: Radio New Zealand International [edited]
<http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=38819>


5 people have died of dysentery in a remote area of Morobe Province
in Papua New Guinea. Health officials had initially thought the 5, in
a village near Bulolo and Wau, had had typhoid, but investigations
revealed it was dysentery.

The Post Courier newspaper reports the Provincial health adviser, Dr.
Likei Theo, saying that medical teams were in February 2008 sent into
the area to verify the disease and determine the causes. He says the
outbreak was caused by the village water supply being contaminated
with human and animal waste.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett
<promed@promedmail.org>

